 the key to understanding the Great Revolt lies in what he calls the “crimino-national” domain—the overlap between the criminological and the nationalist dimensions of British imperial discourse, and the primary terrain upon which the war of 1936–39 was fought. Kelly’s analysis amounts to a new history of one of the major anticolonial insurgencies of the interwar period and a critical moment in the lead-up to Israel’s founding. The Crime of Nationalism offers crucial lessons for the scholarly understanding of nationalism and insurgency more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aViolencezPalestinexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh  a1930s palestine.  a1930s.  a20th century.  aacademic.  aanalysis.  aanticolonial.  aarab.  abritish rule.  acolonization.  acolony.  acrime.  acriminal law.  adiscourse.  aearly 20th century.  agreat revolt.  aimperial.  ainsurgency.  ainsurgents.  ainterwar.  aisrael.  alaw and order.  alegal issues.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern history.  amodern world.  anational movement.  anationalism.  apalestine.  apalestinian history.  apost colonial.  arebellion.  ascholarly.  asocial studies.  awartime.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029148540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965256?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965256/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-